citeinfo.title: Coast Guard Offshore Traffic Separation

descript.abstract: This layer represents Offshore Traffic Separation Schemes as specified by the U.S. Coast Guard in the 2006 Code of Federal Regulations, Title 33, Part 167 - Navigation and Navigable Waters.
descript.purpose:
The purpose of this data is to provide a single map layer covering the Offshore Traffic Separation Schemes and Precautionary Areas for the United States as contained in the Code of Federal Regulation documentation.
An offshore Traffic Separation Scheme (TSS) is a designated routing measure which is aimed at the separation of opposing streams of traffic by appropriate means and by the establishment of traffic lanes. A Precautionary Area is a routing measure comprising an area within defined limits where ships must navigate with particular caution and within which the direction of traffic flow may be recommended. Traffic separation schemes and precautionary areas are established to provide access routes for vessels proceeding to and from U.S. ports.

dataqual.logic:
This data was digitized manually from textual descriptions of the Coast Guard Offshore Traffic Separation Schemes taken from the United States Code of Federal Regulations, Title 33, Part 167. Geographic coordinates are defined using North American 1927 Datum (NAD 27) unless otherwise indicated in the Code of Federal Regulations.
The accuracy of this data depends on the clarity of the written description from the Code of Federal Regulations and the amount and quality of collateral data that may have been used. Textual descriptions of latitudes and longitudes are provided at a granularity of one second. Should any errors be found, please report them to the USCG OSC Customer Support.
